---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "I found live termites in my Darwin home &mdash; what should I do right now?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Do not disturb them. Do not spray them with fly spray, do not break open the mud or galleries, and do not knock down the workings. Disturbed termites abandon that area and re-route through the building, making the colony harder to find and treat and often spreading the damage. Photograph what you can see without touching it, close the area off from pets and kids, and call a licensed NT pest contractor for an urgent same-day or next-day inspection. In Darwin's extreme-pressure environment &mdash; especially if it is Mastotermes &mdash; days matter."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Why must I not spray or disturb active termites before treatment?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Modern colony-elimination treatments (Termidor SC, Sentricon Always Active) rely on undisturbed termites carrying the active ingredient back to the nest and transferring it through the colony. If you spray a contact insecticide or smash the workings, the foraging termites in that zone are killed or driven off, the transfer pathway is broken, and the colony simply re-routes to another part of the structure. You lose the single best opportunity to eliminate the colony, and the technician can no longer use the active site to identify species and entry points."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How fast can a Mastotermes or Coptotermes colony damage a Darwin home?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Faster than almost anywhere else in Australia. Coptotermes acinaciformis can write off structural timbers in 6&ndash;12 months once established. Mastotermes darwiniensis &mdash; the Giant Northern Termite, found only in the Top End and the most destructive termite in Australia &mdash; has enormous colonies, eats almost any cellulose plus rubber, plastic and soft metals, and can cause severe structural loss in a matter of months. That is why active termites in Darwin are an urgent problem, not a 'book it in next month' problem."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Will treating the termites I found stop all the damage?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Treatment eliminates the colony and stops further damage, but it does not repair timber that is already eaten. After colony elimination is confirmed, a separate structural assessment establishes what timber needs replacing. This is why early action matters financially: a colony found and treated in month two costs far less in repairs than the same colony found at month ten. It is also why you should never paint over or patch suspected termite damage before an inspection &mdash; it hides the evidence the technician and your insurer need."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do you offer urgent termite call-outs across Greater Darwin?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. Active termite finds are prioritised for same-day or next-day inspection across the City of Darwin, Palmerston and the Litchfield rural area &mdash; Casuarina, Nightcliff, Marrara, Howard Springs and Humpty Doo included. We confirm species, map the extent, and give you a clear treatment plan and written quote. Call (03) 9003 0108 and tell us you have found live termites so we can prioritise the visit."
      }
    }
